# -*- encoding: utf-8 -*-
# Arc: UnionKingdom | Scene: UnionKingdom6
# Source: C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\The Survival of Sarah Rose\game\script.rpy

translate ru strings:

    old "As the days came and went, they had made good progress."
    new "As the days came and went, they had made good progress."

    old "The rising prosperity of Rosanna had not just brought wealth, it had also brought stability in other areas."
    new "The rising prosperity of Rosanna had not just brought wealth, it had also brought stability in other areas."

    old "Banditry, once a not uncommon threat, was now rare, especially near the coast where she now travelled."
    new "Banditry, once a not uncommon threat, was now rare, especially near the coast where she now travelled."

    old "Of course, a heavily armed caravan like the one she now travelled in was rarely a target for bandits."
    new "Of course, a heavily armed caravan like the one she now travelled in was rarely a target for bandits."

    old "Bandits wanted money above all, and robbing nobles often only invited trouble."
    new "Bandits wanted money above all, and robbing nobles often only invited trouble."

    old "One could rob a dozen farmers and merchants and risk little. Rob one noble, and the soldiers soon followed."
    new "One could rob a dozen farmers and merchants and risk little. Rob one noble, and the soldiers soon followed."

    old "The risk simply didn't weigh up to the rewards."
    new "The risk simply didn't weigh up to the rewards."

    old "Regardless, Sarah was happy to see that the prosperity of her country had not been only restricted to the capital itself."
    new "Regardless, Sarah was happy to see that the prosperity of her country had not been only restricted to the capital itself."

    old "Much of that however changed when they finally reached the borders of Normandi."
    new "Much of that however changed when they finally reached the borders of Normandi."

    old "A smaller country than Rosanna, its lands mainly wrapped around the further Western coastline."
    new "A smaller country than Rosanna, its lands mainly wrapped around the further Western coastline."

    old "Despite its easy access to the sea, the country of Normandi had not seen much benefit from it."
    new "Despite its easy access to the sea, the country of Normandi had not seen much benefit from it."

    old "Where Rosanna's beaches made for easy landing, the sharp rocks and high cliffs of Normandi made for the opposite."
    new "Where Rosanna's beaches made for easy landing, the sharp rocks and high cliffs of Normandi made for the opposite."

    old "Instead, they made perfect homes for smugglers, a business that still thrived to this day."
    new "Instead, they made perfect homes for smugglers, a business that still thrived to this day."

    old "A troublesome problem, had the government of the country given it any mind."
    new "A troublesome problem, had the government of the country given it any mind."

    old "Instead, Normandi was a nation of two worlds."
    new "Instead, Normandi was a nation of two worlds."

    old "The capital of Delphine, and the rest of the country."
    new "The capital of Delphine, and the rest of the country."

    old "It was the former that only ever concerned the nation's nobility, whereas the latter was of a second concern."
    new "It was the former that only ever concerned the nation's nobility, whereas the latter was of a second concern."

    old "Delphine, the largest city in any of the Union Kingdoms, was an impressive metropolis situated upriver from the coast."
    new "Delphine, the largest city in any of the Union Kingdoms, was an impressive metropolis situated upriver from the coast."

    old "As far as the history books were concerned, the city had always existed."
    new "As far as the history books were concerned, the city had always existed."

    old "In all the world, there were other cities that rivalled it, but on this side of the sea, it stood alone."
    new "In all the world, there were other cities that rivalled it, but on this side of the sea, it stood alone."

    old "Given its vast size, it was home to unique talents from across the Union."
    new "Given its vast size, it was home to unique talents from across the Union."

    old "Home to all the greatest Artisans and Craftsmen that the Union knew."
    new "Home to all the greatest Artisans and Craftsmen that the Union knew."

    old "And so, thought the nobility that also lived there, why concern ourselves with anything beyond the limits of the city?"
    new "And so, thought the nobility that also lived there, why concern ourselves with anything beyond the limits of the city?"

    old "Why worry about the lot of farmers and smugglers, when instead we can worry about the blacksmith and the gemcarvers."
    new "Why worry about the lot of farmers and smugglers, when instead we can worry about the blacksmith and the gemcarvers."

    old "As soon as she had crossed the border, the change had been instant."
    new "As soon as she had crossed the border, the change had been instant."

    old "Lands laid fallow and unworked. The roads quickly worsened."
    new "Lands laid fallow and unworked. The roads quickly worsened."

    old "Off in the distance, Sarah could see smoke rising, though she couldn't yet tell what it was."
    new "Off in the distance, Sarah could see smoke rising, though she couldn't yet tell what it was."

    old "She didn't fear, she was far too well guarded, but she did worry for the people of the land that now seemed so dead."
    new "She didn't fear, she was far too well guarded, but she did worry for the people of the land that now seemed so dead."

    old "Further in the distance, she saw a forest, swathes of cut down trees left strewn about."
    new "Further in the distance, she saw a forest, swathes of cut down trees left strewn about."

    old "For nearly a day they passed through the borderlands between their countries, drawing deeper into the territory of Normandi."
    new "For nearly a day they passed through the borderlands between their countries, drawing deeper into the territory of Normandi."

    old "Two days after crossing the border, her carriage suddenly halted."
    new "Two days after crossing the border, her carriage suddenly halted."

    old "Suddenly, she could hear shouting."
    new "Suddenly, she could hear shouting."

    old "Opening the door to her carriage, Sarah stepped out onto the road."
    new "Opening the door to her carriage, Sarah stepped out onto the road."

    old "Your Grace! Please, remain in the carriage where it is safe!"
    new "Your Grace! Please, remain in the carriage where it is safe!"

    old "Sarah disregarded the man's pleading and continued to walk towards the sounds."
    new "Sarah disregarded the man's pleading and continued to walk towards the sounds."

    old "Shouting. Yelling. But it did not seem to her as fighting, perhaps only an argument?"
    new "Shouting. Yelling. But it did not seem to her as fighting, perhaps only an argument?"

    old "Sarah saw Lily come up besides her."
    new "Sarah saw Lily come up besides her."

    old "Be careful. If fighting breaks out, stay behind me."
    new "Be careful. If fighting breaks out, stay behind me."

    old "Sarah nodded, grateful for her friend."
    new "Sarah nodded, grateful for her friend."

    old "As she passed the wagons and reached the front, Sarah finally saw the source of the noise."
    new "As she passed the wagons and reached the front, Sarah finally saw the source of the noise."

    old "The guard captain stood in the center of the road."
    new "The guard captain stood in the center of the road."

    old "Drop your blade or you both will be sorry!"
    new "Drop your blade or you both will be sorry!"

    old "His voice was loud and commanding."
    new "His voice was loud and commanding."

    old "Opposite of him, Sarah saw only a young boy."
    new "Opposite of him, Sarah saw only a young boy."

    old "Please, there is no need for conflict! If you'll just let me explain-"
    new "Please, there is no need for conflict! If you'll just let me explain-"

    old "There are no words to be had!"
    new "There are no words to be had!"

    old "This is a royal convoy and you either do as I say or we'll cut through the both of you!"
    new "This is a royal convoy and you either do as I say or we'll cut through the both of you!"

    old "Standing a little further behind the young squire, Sarah saw another man."
    new "Standing a little further behind the young squire, Sarah saw another man."

    old "Clad in the armor of a knight from head to toe, a scrap of yellow cloth clinging to his steel."
    new "Clad in the armor of a knight from head to toe, a scrap of yellow cloth clinging to his steel."

    old "Other than the cloth, only the blood on the armor gave the knight any colour."
    new "Other than the cloth, only the blood on the armor gave the knight any colour."

    old "Strewn about the knight, bodies. So many bodies."
    new "Strewn about the knight, bodies. So many bodies."

    old "A soft buzzing of flies already descending on the dead could be heard in between the shouting."
    new "A soft buzzing of flies already descending on the dead could be heard in between the shouting."

    old "Drop your sword!"
    new "Drop your sword!"

    old "If you seek to harm my Master...I cannot sheathe my blade. My vow forbids it."
    new "If you seek to harm my Master...I cannot sheathe my blade. My vow forbids it."

    old "Very well, have it your way! Boys!"
    new "Very well, have it your way! Boys!"

    old "The other soldiers moved forward."
    new "The other soldiers moved forward."

    old "Stop!"
    new "Stop!"

    old "Sarah's voice rang out and all were silenced, their eyes falling on her."
    new "Sarah's voice rang out and all were silenced, their eyes falling on her."

    old "What is the meaning of all this? Must we settle every discord with bloodshed?"
    new "What is the meaning of all this? Must we settle every discord with bloodshed?"

    old "Your Grace...please return to your carriage, it is not safe here, these bandits-"
    new "Your Grace...please return to your carriage, it is not safe here, these bandits-"

    old "We are not bandits!"
    new "We are not bandits!"

    old "These troublemakers then! They are blocking the road!"
    new "These troublemakers then! They are blocking the road!"

    old "We were not blocking the road! We came upon these bandits a mere moment before you arrived."
    new "We were not blocking the road! We came upon these bandits a mere moment before you arrived."

    old "Had it not been for this unfortunate timing, my Master and I would have cleared the road!"
    new "Had it not been for this unfortunate timing, my Master and I would have cleared the road!"

    old "The Guard Captain spat on the ground."
    new "The Guard Captain spat on the ground."

    old "Damned lies! Look at those dead men, dressed like farmers. Whose to say you are not the bandit?"
    new "Damned lies! Look at those dead men, dressed like farmers. Whose to say you are not the bandit?"

    old "Sarah stepped forward."
    new "Sarah stepped forward."

    old "Please, captain, sheathe your sword."
    new "Please, captain, sheathe your sword."

    old "Reluctantly, the captain obeyed her command."
    new "Reluctantly, the captain obeyed her command."

    old "Sarah turned to the young man."
    new "Sarah turned to the young man."

    old "Now please, sheathe yours in turn. I promise nothing will come to you."
    new "Now please, sheathe yours in turn. I promise nothing will come to you."

    old "The squire held his sword a moment longer."
    new "The squire held his sword a moment longer."

    old "And my Master?"
    new "And my Master?"

    old "None to him as well, should you each be innocent as you claim."
    new "None to him as well, should you each be innocent as you claim."

    old "Finally, the squire sheathed his blade as well."
    new "Finally, the squire sheathed his blade as well."

    old "Behind him, Sarah saw that the knight that the boy called his master sat down on a rock at the side of the road."
    new "Behind him, Sarah saw that the knight that the boy called his master sat down on a rock at the side of the road."

    old "Come join us good Sir, so we might put this matter to rest with words instead of bloodshed."
    new "Come join us good Sir, so we might put this matter to rest with words instead of bloodshed."

    old "The knight remained still, more statue than man."
    new "The knight remained still, more statue than man."

    old "The squire stepped forward."
    new "The squire stepped forward."

    old "Forgive the manners of my Master...who do I have the honor of adressing, my Lady?"
    new "Forgive the manners of my Master...who do I have the honor of adressing, my Lady?"

    old "Sarah Rose, ruler of Rosanna."
    new "Sarah Rose, ruler of Rosanna."

    old "Instantly the squire fell into a quick bow."
    new "Instantly the squire fell into a quick bow."

    old "My lady, forgive my poor appearance."
    new "My lady, forgive my poor appearance."

    old "Please, it is alright. Rise and instead tell me your name and tell us why your Master insults us by refusing to speak with us."
    new "Please, it is alright. Rise and instead tell me your name and tell us why your Master insults us by refusing to speak with us."

    old "The squire looked anxiously towards the knight."
    new "The squire looked anxiously towards the knight."

    old "My name is Damian. I am in service as squire to my Master."
    new "My name is Damian. I am in service as squire to my Master."

    old "Unfortunately, my Master has taken a vow-of-silence. He will not speak to anyone, not even myself."
    new "Unfortunately, my Master has taken a vow-of-silence. He will not speak to anyone, not even myself."

    old "Sarah looked at the knight, still sitting, unmoving."
    new "Sarah looked at the knight, still sitting, unmoving."

    old "Can you tell me your Master's name? Where he gained his knighthood?"
    new "Can you tell me your Master's name? Where he gained his knighthood?"

    old "Sir Goderic, Knight-Of-The-Fields. I pray forgiveness, for I do not know where or by whom he gained his knighthood."
    new "Sir Goderic, Knight-Of-The-Fields. I pray forgiveness, for I do not know where or by whom he gained his knighthood."

    old "Sarah again studied the knight."
    new "Sarah again studied the knight."

    old "His full-plated suit of armor was clearly expensive."
    new "His full-plated suit of armor was clearly expensive."

    old "Though he was worn and battered, the armor was relatively well maintained."
    new "Though he was worn and battered, the armor was relatively well maintained."

    old "Equipment like that was so expensive that even an entire farming village wouldn't be able to afford it."
    new "Equipment like that was so expensive that even an entire farming village wouldn't be able to afford it."

    old "If you can tell me so little of your Master, tell me then what is your purpose here. Why is the road littered in the bodies of these men?"
    new "If you can tell me so little of your Master, tell me then what is your purpose here. Why is the road littered in the bodies of these men?"

    old "Damian bowed."
    new "Damian bowed."

    old "Of course, my Lady."
    new "Of course, my Lady."

    old "Sir Goderic found me, some three-years ago when my village was attacked by bandits."
    new "Sir Goderic found me, some three-years ago when my village was attacked by bandits."

    old "I had hidden among the rubble, but I was too fearful to leave my hiding place."
    new "I had hidden among the rubble, but I was too fearful to leave my hiding place."

    old "Eventually, after many days, lack of water and food drove me to take a risk I knew I should not have."
    new "Eventually, after many days, lack of water and food drove me to take a risk I knew I should not have."

    old "The bandits, still in the town, captured me."
    new "The bandits, still in the town, captured me."

    old "A knife to my throat, I was all but done, my Lady."
    new "A knife to my throat, I was all but done, my Lady."

    old "But by divine hand, Sir Goderic arrived."
    new "But by divine hand, Sir Goderic arrived."

    old "He alone cut down five men, as though they were nothing but wheat before the scythe."
    new "He alone cut down five men, as though they were nothing but wheat before the scythe."

    old "In their panic they released me and I begged for his protection."
    new "In their panic they released me and I begged for his protection."

    old "He told me that to ask for protection was foolish, because he would not always be there."
    new "He told me that to ask for protection was foolish, because he would not always be there."

    old "Instead, he told me that I should have asked to learn how to defend myself."
    new "Instead, he told me that I should have asked to learn how to defend myself."

    old "You say Sir Goderic told you?"
    new "You say Sir Goderic told you?"

    old "Back then, my Master had not yet taken his vow-of-silence."
    new "Back then, my Master had not yet taken his vow-of-silence."

    old "I see. Continue."
    new "I see. Continue."

    old "Well, I did as Sir Goderic asked and begged him to teach me how to fight."
    new "Well, I did as Sir Goderic asked and begged him to teach me how to fight."

    old "Ever since, I have been his loyal squire, or as loyal as any could hope to be."
    new "Ever since, I have been his loyal squire, or as loyal as any could hope to be."

    old "There was something odd about the thing."
    new "There was something odd about the thing."

    old "Knights often came from nobility. They needed to in order to be trained from youth in the skills required of a knight."
    new "Knights often came from nobility. They needed to in order to be trained from youth in the skills required of a knight."

    old "Additionally, the expense of the suit of armor, also meant that knights rarely hailed from poor backgrounds."
    new "Additionally, the expense of the suit of armor, also meant that knights rarely hailed from poor backgrounds."

    old "Squires, thus, were nearly always the sons of noble houses. Those sons too far in line to inherit much of anything, and so instead, tasked with seeking glory."
    new "Squires, thus, were nearly always the sons of noble houses. Those sons too far in line to inherit much of anything, and so instead, tasked with seeking glory."

    old "Instead, this Sir Goderic had taken a poor farmer boy for a squire."
    new "Instead, this Sir Goderic had taken a poor farmer boy for a squire."

    old "What brought Sir Goderic to your village in the first place?"
    new "What brought Sir Goderic to your village in the first place?"

    old "Ah, I see."
    new "Ah, I see."

    old "See what?"
    new "See what?"

    old "I had forgotten that you were not from here, forgive my mistake, Lady Rose."
    new "I had forgotten that you were not from here, forgive my mistake, Lady Rose."

    old "Sir Goderic is famous in these parts."
    new "Sir Goderic is famous in these parts."

    old "He has taken to ridding these provinces of bandits and their ilk. He has been fighting them for years."
    new "He has taken to ridding these provinces of bandits and their ilk. He has been fighting them for years."

    old "It is that very task that I now aid him in, Gods willing."
    new "It is that very task that I now aid him in, Gods willing."

    old "Sarah looked out across the bodies of the men on the road."
    new "Sarah looked out across the bodies of the men on the road."

    old "And these men you would claim to be bandits then?"
    new "And these men you would claim to be bandits then?"

    old "Yes, my Lady."
    new "Yes, my Lady."

    old "Sarah gestured at the bodies."
    new "Sarah gestured at the bodies."

    old "They are dressed little different than farmers. Merchants. Tell me how I know these to be bandits and not victims?"
    new "They are dressed little different than farmers. Merchants. Tell me how I know these to be bandits and not victims?"

    old "Of course, Lady Rose, you need not take my word for it."
    new "Of course, Lady Rose, you need not take my word for it."

    old "Tell me, what are the tools of a farmer and a merchant?"
    new "Tell me, what are the tools of a farmer and a merchant?"

    old "I did not ask for riddles, but answers."
    new "I did not ask for riddles, but answers."

    old "Of course, my Lady, but what I mean to get at is that a farmer carries a scythe and a merchant perhaps has his wagon and his wares, yes?"
    new "Of course, my Lady, but what I mean to get at is that a farmer carries a scythe and a merchant perhaps has his wagon and his wares, yes?"

    old "Very well, turn over their bodies and you will find evidence of their nature."
    new "Very well, turn over their bodies and you will find evidence of their nature."

    old "Sarah gestured and her men began to turn over the bodies."
    new "Sarah gestured and her men began to turn over the bodies."

    old "One by one, they produced crude swords and daggers. And, poor as it was, improvised armor."
    new "One by one, they produced crude swords and daggers. And, poor as it was, improvised armor."

    old "These men were dressed for battle, as best as poor men could be."
    new "These men were dressed for battle, as best as poor men could be."

    old "Their mistake, it seemed now clear, was thinking that their numbers weighed up against the skill and armor of a trained knight and squire."
    new "Their mistake, it seemed now clear, was thinking that their numbers weighed up against the skill and armor of a trained knight and squire."

    old "Very well."
    new "Very well."

    old "This does not prove beyond a doubt that they are bandits, but I suppose the evidence weighs more in that direction than any other."
    new "This does not prove beyond a doubt that they are bandits, but I suppose the evidence weighs more in that direction than any other."

    old "And you each seem trustworthy, as much as I can make of your Master, the statue."
    new "And you each seem trustworthy, as much as I can make of your Master, the statue."

    old "The knight still sat in place, as if he had not moved so much as a fraction of an inch."
    new "The knight still sat in place, as if he had not moved so much as a fraction of an inch."

    old "The blood on his armor had turned a deep dark brown in the sun."
    new "The blood on his armor had turned a deep dark brown in the sun."

    old "Thank you for your trust, Lady Rose."
    new "Thank you for your trust, Lady Rose."

    old "We pray only that you allow us to continue on our quest to rid these provinces of bandits."
    new "We pray only that you allow us to continue on our quest to rid these provinces of bandits."

    old "We will not trouble you a moment more."
    new "We will not trouble you a moment more."

    old "Very well. Clear the road and we shall each make no more trouble for the other."
    new "Very well. Clear the road and we shall each make no more trouble for the other."

    old "With that, Damian began to drag the bodies of the bandits to the side of the road."
    new "With that, Damian began to drag the bodies of the bandits to the side of the road."

    old "All the while, the knight sat motionless and regarded the scene."
    new "All the while, the knight sat motionless and regarded the scene."

    old "Just before returning to her carriage, Sarah turned towards the Knight-Of-The-Fields."
    new "Just before returning to her carriage, Sarah turned towards the Knight-Of-The-Fields."

    old "Sir Goderic, if the words of your squire are as true as I imagine them to be, you are a true friend to the people of this province."
    new "Sir Goderic, if the words of your squire are as true as I imagine them to be, you are a true friend to the people of this province."

    old "I shall pray for your safety and success."
    new "I shall pray for your safety and success."

    old "The knight's stoic posture was suddenly broken, as wordlessly he bowed down. As much gratitude as a voiceless man could communicate."
    new "The knight's stoic posture was suddenly broken, as wordlessly he bowed down. As much gratitude as a voiceless man could communicate."

    old "Sarah returned to her carriage and they went back on their way."
    new "Sarah returned to her carriage and they went back on their way."

    old "For the rest of the day, Sarah wondered what to make of the whole affair."
    new "For the rest of the day, Sarah wondered what to make of the whole affair."

    old "Having made good progress, Sarah had for a moment imagined her trip to Normandi to be divinely blessed."
    new "Having made good progress, Sarah had for a moment imagined her trip to Normandi to be divinely blessed."

    old "No sooner had the thought crossed her mind when a loud crack announced the breaking of a spoke."
    new "No sooner had the thought crossed her mind when a loud crack announced the breaking of a spoke."

    old "The poor quality of the roads had finally collected its due."
    new "The poor quality of the roads had finally collected its due."

    old "By the groaning sounds of her soldiers, Sarah knew that the matter was not an emergency."
    new "By the groaning sounds of her soldiers, Sarah knew that the matter was not an emergency."

    old "Rather, it would just prove to be a great deal of time and energy that each had hoped to avoid."
    new "Rather, it would just prove to be a great deal of time and energy that each had hoped to avoid."

    old "Sarah stepped out from the cart onto the road."
    new "Sarah stepped out from the cart onto the road."

    old "If not for the trouble with the broken wheel, it was a perfectly lovely day."
    new "If not for the trouble with the broken wheel, it was a perfectly lovely day."

    old "She had taken no more than a few steps before she could hear gravel cracking against metal boots."
    new "She had taken no more than a few steps before she could hear gravel cracking against metal boots."

    old "Always so close by."
    new "Always so close by."

    old "Well, I'd be a rather poor bodyguard if I wasn't."
    new "Well, I'd be a rather poor bodyguard if I wasn't."

    old "I don't think I'm in much danger."
    new "I don't think I'm in much danger."

    old "She gestured towards the small army of soldiers that guarded her. No bandit would be foolish enough to try anything."
    new "She gestured towards the small army of soldiers that guarded her. No bandit would be foolish enough to try anything."

    old "Well, I worry. Even when I don't have to."
    new "Well, I worry. Even when I don't have to."

    old "I guess that's also part of the job."
    new "I guess that's also part of the job."

    old "Sarah smiled. She couldn't really fault the girl for taking her role as serious as she should."
    new "Sarah smiled. She couldn't really fault the girl for taking her role as serious as she should."

    old "Well, I suppose I should give you something to do then."
    new "Well, I suppose I should give you something to do then."

    old "Sarah looked at the front wagon, partially keeled over from the splintered wheel."
    new "Sarah looked at the front wagon, partially keeled over from the splintered wheel."

    old "I don't think we'll be going anywhere just yet. How about you accompany me?"
    new "I don't think we'll be going anywhere just yet. How about you accompany me?"

    old "It would be better to stay with the wagon. With the rest of the soldiers."
    new "It would be better to stay with the wagon. With the rest of the soldiers."

    old "Yes, and it would be better if we turn about and make back for Castle Reinmeer."
    new "Yes, and it would be better if we turn about and make back for Castle Reinmeer."

    old "Then we can lock me up in the dungeon and you stand guard at the door, and we'll make sure nothing ever happens to me."
    new "Then we can lock me up in the dungeon and you stand guard at the door, and we'll make sure nothing ever happens to me."

    old "But life, my good friend, is risk."
    new "But life, my good friend, is risk."

    old "Lily groaned."
    new "Lily groaned."

    old "You know, you could just keep the speech to yourself."
    new "You know, you could just keep the speech to yourself."

    old "You're the ruler, you tell me what to do and I'll do it, even if I don't agree."
    new "You're the ruler, you tell me what to do and I'll do it, even if I don't agree."

    old "So loyal. Give me a thousand of you and I'll conquer the world."
    new "So loyal. Give me a thousand of you and I'll conquer the world."

    old "Lily looked at her, half-amused."
    new "Lily looked at her, half-amused."

    old "You can barely handle one of me."
    new "You can barely handle one of me."

    old "Sarah stepped off the road, heading into the fields next to it."
    new "Sarah stepped off the road, heading into the fields next to it."

    old "The fields of grass grew so thick here that she could see the movements of the wind, dancing atop it."
    new "The fields of grass grew so thick here that she could see the movements of the wind, dancing atop it."

    old "In among the great fields of grass, bright flowers of varying colours, but most of all the famous 'Royal Lavula'."
    new "In among the great fields of grass, bright flowers of varying colours, but most of all the famous 'Royal Lavula'."

    old "The flower was famous for its deep purple, appearing in nearly every field in Normandi."
    new "The flower was famous for its deep purple, appearing in nearly every field in Normandi."

    old "Many kings and queens of the country had taken the flower and its colour for their own, thus giving the flower its royal moniker."
    new "Many kings and queens of the country had taken the flower and its colour for their own, thus giving the flower its royal moniker."

    old "Rosanna, by contrast, valued the rose above all."
    new "Rosanna, by contrast, valued the rose above all."

    old "Sarah could only smile at how even something so small and trivial as a flower could give rise to disagreement."
    new "Sarah could only smile at how even something so small and trivial as a flower could give rise to disagreement."

    old "Moving a ways through the field, she found herself instinctively drawn to a tree that stood out alone from any other."
    new "Moving a ways through the field, she found herself instinctively drawn to a tree that stood out alone from any other."

    old "Sarah swiftly cut through the grass and made her way for it."
    new "Sarah swiftly cut through the grass and made her way for it."

    old "Wait up, Sarah!"
